Here's the recommended approach using **Window lifecycle events** and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom `Window` subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            note.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}
```

### 3. Wire up the ViewModel

```csharp
// NoteViewModel.cs
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = string.Empty;
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Guidance |
|---|---|
| **Where to save** | `OnStopped` — fires when the app is no longer visible |
| **Where to restore** | `OnResumed` — fires when returning from background |
| **Android back button** | Also save in `OnDestroying` — back can skip `Stopped` |
| **Keep it fast** | `Preferences` is ideal for small strings; avoid DB writes here |
| **First launch** | `Resumed` does **not** fire on initial launch; load saved drafts in your page's `OnAppearing` or constructor instead |
